  "prompt": "How Indian Air Force Chief SP Tyagi was involved in Augusta Westland Scam?",
  "response": "Air Chief Marshal S.P. Tyagi, a former Chief of the Indian Air Force, was allegedly involved in the AgustaWestland scam, which pertains to the procurement of 12 VVIP helicopters from AgustaWestland, a subsidiary of the Italian company Finmeccanica, for the Indian Air Force. The deal, valued at approximately EUR 560 million, was signed in 2010.\n\nThe controversy arose when Italian authorities began investigating allegations of corruption and bribery in the deal. As per the allegations, senior officials in India, including Tyagi, were accused of receiving kickbacks to influence the decision-making process, specifically to lower the flying altitude requirement of the helicopters, which subsequently allowed AgustaWestland to qualify for the tender.\n\nTyagi and his cousins were alleged to have met with middlemen and influential individuals to ensure AgustaWestland's selection. Investigations by the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) and the Enforcement Directorate (ED) in India focused on the financial transactions and communications that suggested the involvement of Indian officials in the scandal.\n\nIt is important to note that legal proceedings concerning such high-profile cases can be complex and lengthy. Tyagi has consistently denied any wrongdoing, and the case has involved legal battles over jurisdiction and substantial evidence gathering. For the most current and detailed information, one should refer to the latest updates from credible news sources or official legal documents.",
